Averaged across four decades of NBA playoffs, the arena a game is played in has mattered more to the outcome than the quality gap between the two teams, at least among the factors this analysis could measure.
Home court is supposed to matter most here, in the games with the highest stakes, and for a long time it did exactly that.
Then it started slipping, and the way it slipped is the surprise.
The playoff decline is not about better teams winning more at home.
It is about worse teams winning less.

The shared backdrop first: home court advantage has been shrinking since the 1980s, in the playoffs from nearly << f("po.hw_first_plain") >> to << f("po.hw_last_plain") >> and in the regular season from about << f("reg.hw_first_plain") >> to << f("reg.hw_last_plain") >>.
The playoffs are not just a shrunken copy of the regular season, though.
They have their own structure, their own baseline, and their own timeline of decline.

## How a series is shaped

The home team usually wins Games 1 and 2 at the higher seed's arena, and Game 5, back at the top seed, is the most lopsided game of the series.
Games 3 and 4, at the lower seed's arena, average about 55% for the home team across all decades, though as the next section shows that flat average hides a large change underneath it.
Even Game 7 still goes to the home team about 64% of the time.
Road teams show no evidence of adapting as a series deepens; the last game of a series is nearly as friendly to the host as the first.

